Here is an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP:

**search.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database
$conn = mysqli_connect("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

// Check connection
if (!$conn) {
    die("Connection failed: " . mysqli_connect_error());
}

?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            height: 30px;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<form id="search-form">
    <input type="text" id="search-input" placeholder="Search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<div id="results"></div>

<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
<script>
    $(document).ready(function() {
        $("#search-form").submit(function(event) {
            event.preventDefault();
            var searchQuery = $("#search-input").val().trim();
            if (searchQuery !== "") {
                $.ajax({
                    type: "POST",
                    url: "search.php",
                    data: { query: searchQuery },
                    success: function(data) {
                        $("#results").html(data);
                    }
                });
            }
        });
    });
</script>

<?php
// Query database for results
$query = $_POST['query'];
if ($query !== "") {
    $sql = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$query%' LIMIT 10";
    $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);
    while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
        echo "<p>" . $row['column_name'] . "</p>";
    }
}
?>
</body>
</html>
```
**Explanation:**

This code creates a simple search bar that sends an AJAX request to the same PHP file when the user submits the form. The PHP script then queries the database for results based on the search query and displays them in the `#results` div.

**Note:** This is a basic example, you should consider using prepared statements to prevent SQL injection attacks.

You will need to replace:

* `localhost`, `username`, `password`, and `database` with your actual database credentials.
* `table_name` and `column_name` with the actual table and column names in your database.
* The JavaScript code assumes that you have jQuery loaded, if not, you can include it by adding `<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>` to your HTML head.

Also, this example uses a simple `LIKE` query, which may not be efficient for large databases. You should consider using a more advanced search algorithm or indexing system depending on your specific requirements.

